After applying the analytic finite-size corrections based on the missing-small-q integrals \Delta_{N} and extrapolating variational Monte Carlo (VMC) results for the homogeneous unpolarized two-dimensional electron gas to N\rightarrow\infty, the reported thermodynamic-limit VMC estimates are:
      - For r_{s}=1: Z_{\rm VMC}=0.62(4) and m^{*}/m_{\rm VMC}=1.26(7);
      - For r_{s}=3: Z_{\rm VMC}=0.34(3) and m^{*}/m_{\rm VMC}=1.39(8);
      - For r_{s}=5: Z_{\rm VMC}=0.22(2) and m^{*}/m_{\rm VMC}=1.54(7);
      - For r_{s}=10: Z_{\rm VMC}=0.090(4) and m^{*}/m_{\rm VMC}=1.72(9).
      Here r_{s}=(\pi n a_{B}^{2})^{-1/2} is the dimensionless density parameter and a_{B}=\hbar^{2}/(m e^{2}) the Bohr radius. These VMC thermodynamic-limit values give systematically smaller renormalization factors Z and larger effective masses m^{*} than the corresponding perturbative random-phase-approximation (RPA) values at the same densities, for which the RPA table values are Z_{\rm RPA}=0.66,0.44,0.34,0.24 and m^{*}/m_{\rm RPA}=1.02,1.12,1.16,1.21 for r_{s}=1,3,5,10 respectively.
